# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wifi-standards
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The standards are created and maintained by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) LAN/MAN Standards Committee (IEEE 802).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The base version of the standard was released in 1997 and has had subsequent amendments.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] While each amendment is officially revoked when it is incorporated in the latest version of the standard, the corporate world tends to market to the revisions because they concisely denote the capabilities of their products.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] As a result, in the marketplace, each revision tends to become its own standard.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] **802.11x** is a shorthand for "any version of 802.11", to avoid confusion with "802.11" used specifically for the original 1997 version.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11 uses various radio frequencies, including, but not limited to, 2.4 GHz, 5 GHz, 6 GHz, and 60 GHz frequency bands.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Although IEEE 802.11 specifications list channels that might be used, the allowed radio frequency spectrum availability varies significantly by regulatory domain.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The protocols are typically used on a network stack in conjunction with IEEE 802.2, and are designed to interwork seamlessly with Ethernet, and are very often used to carry Internet Protocol traffic.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11 is also a basis for vehicle-based communication networks with IEEE 802.11p.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The 802.11 family consists of a series of half-duplex over-the-air modulation techniques that use the same basic protocol.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Other standards in the family (c–f, h, j) are service amendments that are used to extend the current scope of the existing standard, which amendments may also include corrections to a previous specification.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11b and 802.11g use the 2.4-GHz ISM band, operating in the United States under Part 15 of the U.S.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Federal Communications Commission Rules and Regulations.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Because of this choice of frequency band, 802.11b/g/n equipment may occasionally suffer interference in the 2.4-GHz band from microwave ovens, cordless telephones, and Bluetooth devices.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11b and 802.11g control their interference and susceptibility to interference by using direct-sequence spread spectrum (DSSS) and orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (OFDM) signaling methods, respectively.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11a uses the 5 GHz U-NII band which, for much of the world, offers at least 23 non-overlapping, 20-MHz-wide channels.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This is an advantage over the 2.4-GHz, ISM-frequency band, which offers only three non-overlapping, 20-MHz-wide channels where other adjacent channels overlap (see: list of WLAN channels).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Better or worse performance with higher or lower frequencies (channels) may be realized, depending on the environment.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11n and 802.11ax can use either the 2.4 GHz or 5 GHz band; 802.11ac uses only the 5 GHz band.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The segment of the radio frequency spectrum used by 802.11 varies between countries.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In the US, 802.11a and 802.11g devices may be operated without a license, as allowed in Part 15 of the FCC Rules and Regulations.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Frequencies used by channels one through six of 802.11b and 802.11g fall within the 2.4 GHz amateur radio band.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Licensed amateur radio operators may operate 802.11b/g devices under Part 97 of the FCC Rules and Regulations, allowing increased power output but not commercial content or encryption.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In 2018, the Wi-Fi Alliance began using a consumer-friendly generation numbering scheme for the publicly used 802.11 protocols.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11 technology has its origins in a 1985 ruling by the U.S.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Federal Communications Commission that released the ISM band for unlicensed use.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In 1991 NCR Corporation/AT&T (now Nokia Labs and LSI Corporation) invented a precursor to 802.11 in Nieuwegein, the Netherlands.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The inventors initially intended to use the technology for cashier systems.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The first wireless products were brought to the market under the name WaveLAN with raw data rates of 1 Mbit/s and 2 Mbit/s.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Vic Hayes, who held the chair of IEEE 802.11 for 10 years, and has been called the "father of Wi-Fi", was involved in designing the initial 802.11b and 802.11a standards within the IEEE.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] He, along with Bell Labs Engineer Bruce Tuch, approached IEEE to create a standard.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In 1999, the Wi-Fi Alliance was formed as a trade association to hold the Wi-Fi trademark under which most products are sold.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The major commercial breakthrough came with Apple's adoption of Wi-Fi for their iBook series of laptops in 1999.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It was the first mass consumer product to offer Wi-Fi network connectivity, which was then branded by Apple as AirPort.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] One year later IBM followed with its ThinkPad 1300 series in 2000.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11y-2008 extended operation of 802.11a to the licensed 3.7 GHz band.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Increased power limits allow a range up to 5,000 m.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] As of 2009, it is only being licensed in the United States by the FCC.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Based on short guard interval; standard guard interval is ~10% slower.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Rates vary widely based on distance, obstructions, and interference.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] For single-user cases only, based on default guard interval which is 0.8 microseconds.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Since multi-user via OFDMA has become available for 802.11ax, these may decrease.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Also, these theoretical values depend on the link distance, whether the link is line-of-sight or not, interferences and the multi-path components in the environment.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The default guard interval is 0.8 microseconds.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] However, 802.11ax extended the maximum available guard interval to 3.2 microseconds, in order to support outdoor communications, where the maximum possible propagation delay is larger compared to Indoor environments.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The original version of the standard IEEE 802.11 was released in 1997 and clarified in 1999, but is now obsolete.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It specified two net bit rates of 1 or 2 megabits per second (Mbit/s), plus forward error correction code.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It specified three alternative physical layer technologies: diffuse infrared operating at 1 Mbit/s; frequency-hopping spread spectrum operating at 1 Mbit/s or 2 Mbit/s; and direct-sequence spread spectrum operating at 1 Mbit/s or 2 Mbit/s.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The latter two radio technologies used microwave transmission over the Industrial Scientific Medical frequency band at 2.4 GHz.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Some earlier WLAN technologies used lower frequencies, such as the U.S.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Legacy 802.11 with direct-sequence spread spectrum was rapidly supplanted and popularized by 802.11b.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11a, published in 1999, uses the same data link layer protocol and frame format as the original standard, but an OFDM based air interface (physical layer) was added.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It operates in the 5 GHz band with a maximum net data rate of 54 Mbit/s, plus error correction code, which yields realistic net achievable throughput in the mid-20 Mbit/s.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It has seen widespread worldwide implementation, particularly within the corporate workspace.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Since the 2.4 GHz band is heavily used to the point of being crowded, using the relatively unused 5 GHz band gives 802.11a a significant advantage.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] However, this high carrier frequency also brings a disadvantage: the effective overall range of 802.11a is less than that of 802.11b/g.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In theory, 802.11a signals are absorbed more readily by walls and other solid objects in their path due to their smaller wavelength, and, as a result, cannot penetrate as far as those of 802.11b.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In practice, 802.11b typically has a higher range at low speeds (802.11b will reduce speed to 5.5 Mbit/s or even 1 Mbit/s at low signal strengths).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11a also suffers from interference, but locally there may be fewer signals to interfere with, resulting in less interference and better throughput.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The 802.11b standard has a maximum raw data rate of 11 Mbit/s (Megabits per second) and uses the same media access method defined in the original standard.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11b products appeared on the market in early 2000, since 802.11b is a direct extension of the modulation technique defined in the original standard.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The dramatic increase in throughput of 802.11b (compared to the original standard), along with simultaneous substantial price reductions, led to the rapid acceptance of 802.11b as the definitive wireless LAN technology.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Devices using 802.11b experience interference from other products operating in the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Devices operating in the 2.4 GHz range include microwave ovens, Bluetooth devices, baby monitors, cordless telephones, and some amateur radio equipment.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] As unlicensed intentional radiators in this ISM band, they must not interfere with and must tolerate interference from primary or secondary allocations (users) of this band, such as amateur radio.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The IEEE 802.11be-2024 amendment was approved by the IEEE SA Standards Board on 26 September 2024 and published on 22 July 2025.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It modifies both the MAC and PHY layers, targeting at least one operating mode with 30 Gbit/s MAC-SAP throughput across 1–7.250 GHz while maintaining coexistence with legacy 802.11 devices in the 2.4, 5 and 6 GHz bands.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In June 2003, a third modulation standard was ratified: 802.11g.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This works in the 2.4 GHz band (like 802.11b), but uses the same OFDM based transmission scheme as 802.11a.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It operates at a maximum physical layer bit rate of 54 Mbit/s exclusive of forward error correction codes, or about 22 Mbit/s average throughput.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11g hardware is fully backward compatible with 802.11b hardware, and therefore is encumbered with legacy issues that reduce throughput by ~21% when compared to 802.11a.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The then-proposed 802.11g standard was rapidly adopted in the market starting in January 2003, well before ratification, due to the desire for higher data rates as well as reductions in manufacturing costs.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] By summer 2003, most dual-band 802.11a/b products became dual-band/tri-mode, supporting a and b/g in a single mobile adapter card or access point.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Details of making b and g work well together occupied much of the lingering technical process; in an 802.11g network, however, the activity of an 802.11b participant will reduce the data rate of the overall 802.11g network.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Like 802.11b, 802.11g devices also suffer interference from other products operating in the 2.4 GHz band, for example, wireless keyboards.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In 2003, task group TGma was authorized to "roll up" many of the amendments to the 1999 version of the 802.11 standard.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] REVma or 802.11ma, as it was called, created a single document that merged 8 amendments (802.11a, b, d, e, g, h, i, j) with the base standard.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Upon approval on 8 March 2007, 802.11REVma was renamed to the then-current base standard **IEEE 802.11-2007**.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11n is an amendment that improves upon the previous 802.11 standards; its first draft of certification was published in 2006.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The 802.11n standard was retroactively labelled as **Wi-Fi 4** by the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The standard added support for multiple-input multiple-output antennas (MIMO).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11n operates on both the 2.4 GHz and the 5 GHz bands.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Its net data rate ranges from 54 Mbit/s to 600 Mbit/s.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The IEEE has approved the amendment, and it was published in October 2009.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Prior to the final ratification, enterprises were already migrating to 802.11n networks based on the Wi-Fi Alliance's certification of products conforming to a 2007 draft of the 802.11n proposal.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Early Intel WiFi cards were not compatible with the final standard.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Many rival access points and cards also did not support 5 GHz at all.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In May 2007, task group TGmb was authorized to "roll up" many of the amendments to the 2007 version of the 802.11 standard.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] REVmb or 802.11mb, as it was called, created a single document that merged ten amendments (802.11k, r, y, n, w, p, z, v, u, s) with the 2007 base standard.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In addition much cleanup was done, including a reordering of many of the clauses.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Upon publication on 29 March 2012, the new standard was referred to as **IEEE 802.11-2012**.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The 802.11ac standard was retroactively labelled as **Wi-Fi 5** by the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Changes compared to 802.11n include wider channels (80 or 160 MHz versus 40 MHz) in the 5 GHz band, more spatial streams (up to eight versus four), higher-order modulation (up to 256-QAM vs.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 64-QAM), and the addition of Multi-user MIMO (MU-MIMO).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance separated the introduction of ac wireless products into two phases ("waves"), named "Wave 1" and "Wave 2".
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] From mid-2013, the alliance started certifying Wave 1 802.11ac products shipped by manufacturers, based on the IEEE 802.11ac Draft 3.0 (the IEEE standard was not finalized until later that year).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In 2016 Wi-Fi Alliance introduced the Wave 2 certification, to provide higher bandwidth and capacity than Wave 1 products.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Wave 2 products include additional features like MU-MIMO, 160 MHz channel width support, support for more 5 GHz channels, and four spatial streams (with four antennas; compared to three in Wave 1 and 802.11n, and eight in IEEE's 802.11ax specification).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11ad is an amendment that defines a new physical layer for 802.11 networks to operate in the 60 GHz millimeter wave spectrum.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This frequency band has significantly different propagation characteristics than the 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz bands where Wi-Fi networks operate.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Products implementing the 802.11ad standard are sold under the WiGig brand name, with a certification program developed by the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The peak transmission rate of 802.11ad is 7 Gbit/s.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The WiGig standard was announced in 2009; IEEE 802.11ad was ratified and published in December 2012.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11ad is used for very high data rates (about 8 Gbit/s) and for short-range communication (about 1–10 meters).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] TP-Link announced the world's first 802.11ad router in January 2016.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11af, also referred to as "White-Fi" and "Super Wi-Fi", is an amendment, approved in February 2014, that allows WLAN operation in TV white space spectrum in the VHF and UHF bands between 54 and 790 MHz.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It uses cognitive radio technology to transmit on unused TV channels, with the standard taking measures to limit interference for primary users, such as analog TV, digital TV, and wireless microphones.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Access points and stations determine their position using a satellite positioning system such as GPS, and use the Internet to query a geolocation database (GDB) provided by a regional regulatory agency to discover what frequency channels are available for use at a given time and position.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The physical layer uses OFDM and is based on 802.11ac.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The propagation path loss as well as the attenuation by materials such as brick and concrete is lower in the UHF and VHF bands than in the 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz bands, which increases the possible range.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The frequency channels are 6 to 8 MHz wide, depending on the regulatory domain.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Up to four channels may be bonded in either one or two contiguous blocks.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] MIMO operation is possible with up to four streams used for either space–time block code (STBC) or multi-user (MU) operation.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The achievable data rate per spatial stream is 26.7 Mbit/s for 6 and 7 MHz channels, and 35.6 Mbit/s for 8 MHz channels.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] With four spatial streams and four bonded channels, the maximum data rate is 426.7 Mbit/s for 6 and 7 MHz channels and 568.9 Mbit/s for 8 MHz channels.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In addition, existing MAC and PHY functions have been enhanced, and obsolete features were removed or marked for removal.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Some clauses and annexes have been renumbered.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11ah, published in 2017, defines a WLAN system operating at sub-1 GHz license-exempt bands.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Due to the favorable propagation characteristics of the low-frequency spectra, 802.11ah can provide improved transmission range compared with the conventional 802.11 WLANs operating in the 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz bands.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11ah can be used for various purposes including large-scale sensor networks, extended-range hotspots, and outdoor Wi-Fi for cellular WAN carrier traffic offloading, whereas the available bandwidth is relatively narrow.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The protocol intends consumption to be competitive with low-power Bluetooth, at a much wider range.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11ai is an amendment to the 802.11 standard that added new mechanisms for a faster initial link setup time.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11aj is a derivative of 802.11ad for use in the 45 GHz unlicensed spectrum available in some regions of the world (specifically China); it also provides additional capabilities for use in the 60 GHz band.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Alternatively known as China Millimeter Wave (CMMW).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11aq is an amendment to the 802.11 standard that will enable pre-association discovery of services.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This extends some of the mechanisms in 802.11u that enabled device discovery to discover further the services running on a device, or provided by a network.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In addition, existing MAC and PHY functions have been enhanced and obsolete features were removed or marked for removal.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Some clauses and annexes have been added.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11ax is the successor to 802.11ac, marketed as **Wi-Fi 6** (2.4 GHz and 5 GHz) and Wi-Fi 6E (6 GHz) by the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It is also known as *High Efficiency* Wi-Fi, for the overall improvements to Wi-Fi 6 clients in *dense environments*.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] For an individual client, the maximum improvement in data rate (PHY speed) against the predecessor (802.11ac) is only 39% (for comparison, this improvement was nearly 500% for the predecessors).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Yet, even with this comparatively minor 39% figure, the goal was to provide *4 times* the throughput-per-area of 802.11ac (hence *High Efficiency*).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The motivation behind this goal was the deployment of WLAN in dense environments such as corporate offices, shopping malls and dense residential apartments.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This is achieved by means of a technique called OFDMA, which is basically multiplexing in the *frequency domain* (as opposed to *spatial* multiplexing, as in 802.11ac).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This is equivalent to cellular technology applied to Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The IEEE 802.11ax‑2021 standard was approved on February 9, 2021.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11ay is a standard that is being developed, also called EDMG: Enhanced Directional MultiGigabit PHY.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It is an amendment that defines a new physical layer for 802.11 networks to operate in the 60 GHz millimeter wave spectrum.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It will be an extension of the existing 11ad, aimed at extending the throughput, range, and use cases.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The main use cases include indoor operation and short-range communications due to atmospheric oxygen absorption and the inability to penetrate walls.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The peak transmission rate of 802.11ay is 40 Gbit/s.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The main extensions include: channel bonding (2, 3 and 4), MIMO (up to 4 streams) and higher modulation schemes.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11ba Wake-up Radio (WUR) Operation is an amendment to the IEEE 802.11 standard that enables energy-efficient operation for data reception without increasing latency.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The target active power consumption to receive a WUR packet is less than 1 milliwatt and supports data rates of 62.5 kbit/s and 250 kbit/s.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The WUR PHY uses MC-OOK (multicarrier OOK) to achieve extremely low power consumption.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11bb is a networking protocol standard in the IEEE 802.11 set of protocols that uses infrared light for communications.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE 802.11be Extremely High Throughput (EHT) is the next amendment to the 802.11 IEEE standard, and is designated as **Wi-Fi 7**.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It builds upon 802.11ax, focusing on WLAN indoor and outdoor operation with stationary and pedestrian speeds in the 2.4 GHz, 5 GHz, and 6 GHz frequency bands.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Across all variations of 802.11, maximum achievable throughputs are given either based on measurements under ideal conditions or in the layer-2 data rates.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] However, this does not apply to typical deployments in which data is being transferred between two endpoints, of which at least one is typically connected to a wired infrastructure, and the other endpoint is connected to an infrastructure via a wireless link.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This means that, typically, data frames pass an 802.11 (WLAN) medium and are being converted to 802.3 (Ethernet) or vice versa.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Due to the difference in the frame (header) lengths of these two media, the application's packet size determines the speed of the data transfer.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This means applications that use small packets (e.g., VoIP) create dataflows with high-overhead traffic (i.e., a low goodput).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Other factors that contribute to the overall application data rate are the speed with which the application transmits the packets (i.e., the data rate) and, of course, the energy with which the wireless signal is received.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The latter is determined by distance and by the configured output power of the communicating devices.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The same references apply to the attached graphs that show measurements of UDP throughput.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Each represents an average (UDP) throughput (please note that the error bars are there but barely visible due to the small variation) of 25 measurements.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Each is with a specific packet size (small or large) and with a specific data rate (10 kbit/s – 100 Mbit/s).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Markers for traffic profiles of common applications are included as well.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] These figures assume there are no packet errors, which, if occurring, will lower the transmission rate further.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] These are commonly referred to as the "2.4 GHz and 5 GHz bands" in most sales literature.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Each spectrum is subdivided into *channels* with a center frequency and bandwidth, analogous to how radio and TV broadcast bands are subdivided.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The 2.4 GHz band is divided into 14 channels spaced 5 MHz apart, beginning with channel 1, which is centered on 2.412 GHz.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The latter channels have additional restrictions or are unavailable for use in some regulatory domains.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The channel numbering of the 5.725–5.875 GHz spectrum is less intuitive due to the differences in regulations between countries.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] These are discussed in greater detail on the list of WLAN channels.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] In addition to specifying the channel center frequency, 802.11 also specifies (in Clause 17) a spectral mask defining the permitted power distribution across each channel.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The mask requires the signal to be attenuated a minimum of 20 dB from its peak amplitude at ±11 MHz from the center frequency, the point at which a channel is effectively 22 MHz wide.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] One consequence is that stations can use only every fourth or fifth channel without overlap.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Availability of channels is regulated by country, constrained in part by how each country allocates radio spectrum to various services.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] At one extreme, Japan permits the use of all 14 channels for 802.11b, and 1–13 for 802.11g/n-2.4.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Other countries such as Spain initially allowed only channels 10 and 11, and France allowed only 10, 11, 12, and 13; however, Europe now allow channels 1 through 13.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] North America and some Central and South American countries allow only 1 through 11.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Since the spectral mask defines only power output restrictions up to ±11 MHz from the center frequency to be attenuated by −50 dBr, it is often assumed that the energy of the channel extends no further than these limits.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It is more correct to say that the overlapping signal on any channel should be sufficiently attenuated to interfere with a transmitter on any other channel minimally, given the separation between channels.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Due to the near–far problem a transmitter can impact (desensitize) a receiver on a "non-overlapping" channel, but only if it is close to the victim receiver (within a meter) or operating above allowed power levels.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Conversely, a sufficiently distant transmitter on an overlapping channel can have little to no significant effect.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Confusion often arises over the amount of channel separation required between transmitting devices.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11b was based on direct-sequence spread spectrum (DSSS) modulation and utilized a channel bandwidth of 22 MHz, resulting in *three* "non-overlapping" channels (1, 6, and 11).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] 802.11g was based on OFDM modulation and utilized a channel bandwidth of 20 MHz.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This occasionally leads to the belief that *four* "non-overlapping" channels (1, 5, 9, and 13) exist under 802.11g.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This does not mean that the technical overlap of the channels recommends the non-use of overlapping channels.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The amount of inter-channel interference seen on a configuration using channels 1, 5, 9, and 13 (which is permitted in Europe, but not in North America) is barely different from a three-channel configuration, but with an entire extra channel.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] However, overlap between channels with more narrow spacing (e.g., 1, 4, 7, 11 in North America) may cause unacceptable degradation of signal quality and throughput, particularly when users transmit near the boundaries of AP cells.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] IEEE uses the phrase *regdomain* to refer to a legal regulatory region.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Different countries define different levels of allowable transmitter power, time that a channel can be occupied, and different available channels.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Domain codes are specified for the United States, Canada, ETSI (Europe), Spain, France, Japan, and China.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Most Wi-Fi certified devices default to *regdomain* 0, which means least common denominator settings, i.e., the device will not transmit at a power above the allowable power in any nation, nor will it use frequencies that are not permitted in any nation.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The *regdomain* setting is often made difficult or impossible to change so that the end-users do not conflict with local regulatory agencies such as the United States' Federal Communications Commission.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Current 802.11 standards specify frame types for use in the transmission of data as well as management and control of wireless links.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Frames are divided into very specific and standardized sections.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Each frame consists of a *MAC header*, *payload*, and *frame check sequence* (FCS).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The first two bytes of the MAC header form a frame control field specifying the form and function of the frame.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The next two bytes are reserved for the Duration ID field, indicating how long the field's transmission will take, so other devices know when the channel will be available again.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] This field can take one of three forms: Duration, Contention-Free Period (CFP), and Association ID (AID).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] An 802.11 frame can have up to four address fields.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Address 1 is the receiver, Address 2 is the transmitter, Address 3 is used for filtering purposes by the receiver.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Address 4 is only present in data frames transmitted between access points in an Extended Service Set or between intermediate nodes in a mesh network.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The payload or frame body field is variable in size, from 0 to 2304 bytes plus any overhead from security encapsulation, and contains information from higher layers.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The Frame Check Sequence (FCS) is the last four bytes in the standard 802.11 frame.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Often referred to as the Cyclic Redundancy Check (CRC), it allows for integrity checks of retrieved frames.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] As frames are about to be sent, the FCS is calculated and appended.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] When a station receives a frame, it can calculate the FCS of the frame and compare it to the one received.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] If they match, it is assumed that the frame was not distorted during transmission.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Management frames are not always authenticated, and allow for the maintenance or discontinuance of communication.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The body of a management frame consists of frame-subtype-dependent fixed fields followed by a sequence of information elements (IEs).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Control frames facilitate the exchange of data frames between stations.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Data frames carry packets from web pages, files, etc., within the body.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] If the OUI is all zeroes, the protocol ID field is an EtherType value.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Almost all 802.11 data frames use 802.2 and SNAP headers, and most use an OUI of 00:00:00 and an EtherType value.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] For the 5.9 GHz PHY (802.11p), the body begins with an EtherType field, and here is no 802.2 header.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] Similar to TCP congestion control on the internet, frame loss is built into the operation of 802.11.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] To select the correct transmission speed or Modulation and Coding Scheme, a rate control algorithm may test different speeds.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] The actual packet loss rate of Access points varies widely for different link conditions.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] There are variations in the loss rate experienced on production Access points, between 10% and 80%, with 30% being a common average.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] It is important to be aware that the link layer should recover these lost frames.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p01] If the sender does not receive an Acknowledgement (ACK) frame, then it will be resent.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] 802.11F and 802.11T are recommended practices rather than standards and are capitalized as such.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] 802.11m is used for standard maintenance.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] Both the terms "standard" and "amendment" are used when referring to the different variants of IEEE standards.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] As far as the IEEE Standards Association is concerned, there is only one current standard; it is denoted by IEEE 802.11 followed by the date published.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] IEEE 802.11-2024 is the only version currently in publication, superseding previous releases.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] The standard is updated by means of amendments.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] Amendments are created by task groups (TG).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] Both the task group and their finished document are denoted by 802.11 followed by one or two lowercase letters, for example, IEEE 802.11a or IEEE 802.11ax.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] Updating 802.11 is the responsibility of task group m.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] In order to create a new version, TGm combines the previous version of the standard and all published amendments.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] TGm also provides clarification and interpretation to industry on published documents.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] Various terms in 802.11 are used to specify aspects of wireless local-area networking operation and may be unfamiliar to some readers.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] For example, *time unit* (usually abbreviated *TU*) is used to indicate a unit of time equal to 1024 microseconds.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] Numerous time constants are defined in terms of TU (rather than the nearly equal millisecond).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] Also, the term *portal* is used to describe an entity that is similar to an 802.1H bridge.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] A portal provides access to the WLAN by non-802.11 LAN STAs.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] Not long after, Adam Stubblefield and AT&T publicly announced the first verification of the attack.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] In the attack, they were able to intercept transmissions and gain unauthorized access to wireless networks.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] The IEEE set up a dedicated task group to create a replacement security solution, 802.11i (previously, this work was handled as part of a broader 802.11e effort to enhance the MAC layer).
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] The Wi-Fi Alliance announced an interim specification called Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) based on a subset of the then-current IEEE 802.11i draft.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] These started to appear in products in mid-2003.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] IEEE 802.11i (also known as WPA2) itself was ratified in June 2004, and uses the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES), instead of RC4, which was used in WEP.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] The modern recommended encryption for the home/consumer space is WPA2 (AES Pre-Shared Key), and for the enterprise space is WPA2 along with a RADIUS authentication server (or another type of authentication server) and a strong authentication method such as EAP-TLS.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] In January 2005, the IEEE set up yet another task group "w" to protect management and broadcast frames, which previously were sent unsecured.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] In December 2011, a security flaw was revealed that affects some wireless routers with a specific implementation of the optional Wi-Fi Protected Setup (WPS) feature.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] While WPS is not a part of 802.11, the flaw allows an attacker within the range of the wireless router to recover the WPS PIN and, with it, the router's 802.11i password in a few hours.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] In late 2014, Apple announced that its iOS 8 mobile operating system would scramble MAC addresses during the pre-association stage to thwart retail footfall tracking made possible by the regular transmission of uniquely identifiable probe requests.
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] Android 8.0 "Oreo" introduced a similar feature, named "MAC randomization".
[src:wifi-standards/ieee-802-11-p02] Wi-Fi users may be subjected to a Wi-Fi deauthentication attack to eavesdrop, attack passwords, or force the use of another, usually more expensive access point.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] This standard aims to boost throughput in crowded places like offices and malls.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] Though the nominal data rate is only 37% higher than that of Wi-Fi 5, the throughput increases by at least four times, making it more efficient and reducing latency by 75%.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] The quintupling of overall throughput is made possible by higher spectral efficiency.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] Wi-Fi 6 has a main feature called OFDMA, similar to how cellular common-carrier networks work.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] This brings better spectrum use, improved power control to avoid interference, and enhancements like 1024‑QAM, MIMO and MU-MIMO for faster speeds.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] There are also reliability improvements such as lower power consumption and security protocols like Target Wake Time and WPA3.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] The 802.11ax standard was approved on September 1, 2020, with Draft 8 getting 95% approval.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] Subsequently, on February 1, 2021, the standard received official endorsement from the IEEE Standards Board.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] With the previous generation Wi-Fi 5, multi-user MIMO was introduced, which is a spatial multiplexing technique.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] MU-MIMO allows the access point to form beams towards each client, while transmitting information simultaneously.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] By doing so, the interference between clients is reduced, and the overall throughput is increased, since multiple clients can receive data simultaneously.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] With Wi-Fi 6, a similar multiplexing is introduced in the *frequency-division multiplexing*: OFDMA.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] With OFDMA, multiple clients are assigned to different Resource Units in the available spectrum.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] By doing so, an 80 MHz channel can be split into multiple Resource Units, so that multiple clients receive different types of data over the same spectrum, simultaneously.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] To support OFDMA, Wi-Fi 6 needs four times as many subcarriers as Wi-Fi 5.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] Since the available bandwidths have not changed and the number of subcarriers increases by a factor of four, the subcarrier spacing is reduced by the same factor.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] This introduces OFDM symbols that are four times longer: with Wi-Fi 5, an OFDM symbol takes 3.2 microseconds to transmit.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] With Wi-Fi 6, it takes 12.8 microseconds (both without guard intervals).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] The 802.11ax amendment brings several key improvements over 802.11ac.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] While 802.11ac only uses the 5 GHz band, which is a bit over 700 MHz wide, 802.11ax also allows the use of the 2.4 GHz band of some earlier protocols, less than 100 MHz wide, and the larger 6 GHz band, about 1200 MHz wide.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] Wi-Fi 6E adds to Wi‑Fi 6 the use of the 6 GHz band and, thereby, channels that are 160 MHz wide without the restrictions of Dynamic Frequency Selection that apply to all 160 MHz channels in the 5 GHz band.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] The number and selection of channels available depends on the country a given Wi-Fi 6 network operates in.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] To meet the goal of supporting dense 802.11 deployments, the following features have been approved.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] Following the ratification of the IEEE 802.11ax standard in February 2021, Wi-Fi 6 saw rapid adoption across consumer and enterprise devices.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] The Wi-Fi Alliance began certifying Wi-Fi 6 devices under its *Wi-Fi CERTIFIED 6* program in September 2019, ahead of the standard's formal approval.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-6] Major smartphone, laptop, and router manufacturers incorporated Wi-Fi 6 support into their product lines beginning in 2020.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi uses multiple parts of the IEEE 802 protocol family and is designed to work well with its wired sibling, Ethernet.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Compatible devices can network through wireless access points with each other as well as with wired devices and the Internet.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Different versions of Wi-Fi are specified by various IEEE 802.11 protocol standards, with different radio technologies determining radio bands, maximum ranges, and speeds that may be achieved.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi most commonly uses the 2.4 gigahertz (120 mm) UHF and 5 gigahertz (60 mm) SHF radio bands, with the 6 gigahertz SHF band used in newer generations of the standard; these bands are subdivided into multiple channels.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Channels can be shared between networks, but, within range, only one transmitter can transmit on a channel at a time.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi's radio bands work best for line-of-sight use.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Common obstructions, such as walls, pillars, home appliances, etc., may greatly reduce range, but this also helps minimize interference between different networks in crowded environments.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The range of an access point is about 20 m (66 ft) indoors, while some access points claim up to a 150 m (490 ft) range outdoors.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Hotspot coverage can be as small as a single room with walls that block radio waves or as large as many square kilometers using multiple overlapping access points with roaming permitted between them.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Over time, the speed and spectral efficiency of Wi-Fi has increased.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] As of 2025, some versions of Wi-Fi, running on suitable hardware at close range, can achieve speeds of 23 Gbit/s (gigabit per second).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Federal Communications Commission released parts of the ISM bands for unlicensed use for communications in the United States.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] These frequency bands include the same 2.4 GHz bands used by equipment such as microwave ovens, and are thus subject to interference.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In 1991 in the city of Nieuwegein in the Netherlands, the NCR Corporation and AT&T invented the precursor to 802.11, intended for use in cashier systems, under the name WaveLAN.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] NCR's Vic Hayes, who held the chair of IEEE 802.11 for ten years, along with Bell Labs engineer Bruce Tuch, approached the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) to create a standard and were involved in designing the initial 802.11b and 802.11a specifications within the IEEE.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] They have both been subsequently inducted into the Wi-Fi NOW Hall of Fame.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In 1989 in Australia, a team of scientists began working on wireless LAN technology.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A prototype test bed for a wireless local area network (WLAN) was developed in 1992 by a team of researchers from the Radiophysics Division of the CSIRO (Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation) in Australia, led by John O'Sullivan.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A patent for Wi-Fi was lodged by the CSIRO in 1992.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The first version of the 802.11 protocol was released in 1997, and provided up to 2 Mbit/s link speeds.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This was updated in 1999 with 802.11b to permit 11 Mbit/s link speeds.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In 1999, the Wi-Fi Alliance formed as a trade association to hold the Wi-Fi trademark under which most IEEE 802.11 products are sold.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The major commercial breakthrough came with Apple Inc. adopting Wi-Fi for their iBook series of laptops in 1999.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This was in collaboration with the same group that helped create the standard: Vic Hayes, Bruce Tuch, Cees Links, Rich McGinn, and others from Lucent.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In 2000, Radiata, a group of Australian scientists connected to the CSIRO, were the first to use the 802.11a standard on chips connected to a Wi-Fi network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi uses a large number of patents held by multiple different organizations.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Australia, the United States and the Netherlands simultaneously claim the invention of Wi-Fi, and a consensus has not been reached globally.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In 2009, the Australian CSIRO was awarded $200 million after a patent settlement with 14 technology companies, with a further $220 million awarded in 2012 after legal proceedings with 23 companies.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In 2016, the CSIRO's WLAN prototype test bed was chosen as Australia's contribution to the exhibition *A History of the World in 100 Objects* held in the National Museum of Australia.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The name *Wi-Fi*, commercially used as early as August 1999, was coined by the brand-consulting firm Interbrand.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance had hired Interbrand to create a name that was "a little catchier than 'IEEE 802.11b Direct Sequence'." According to Phil Belanger, a founding member of the Wi-Fi Alliance, the term *Wi-Fi* was chosen from a list of ten names that Interbrand proposed.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The yin-yang Wi-Fi logo indicates the certification of a product for interoperability.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The name is often written as *WiFi*, *Wifi*, or *wifi*, but these are not approved by the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] IEEE, a separate but related organization, has stated "WiFi is a short name for Wireless Fidelity" on their website.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The name *Wi-Fi* was partly chosen because it sounds similar to Hi-Fi, which consumers take to mean *high fidelity* or *high quality*.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Interbrand hoped consumers would find the name catchy, and that they would assume this *wireless* protocol has high fidelity because of its name.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Other technologies intended for fixed points, including Motorola Canopy, are usually called *fixed wireless*.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Alternative wireless technologies include Zigbee, Z-Wave, Bluetooth and mobile phone standards.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] To connect to a Wi-Fi LAN, a computer must be equipped with a wireless network interface controller.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The combination of a computer and an interface controller is called a *station*.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Stations are identified by one or more MAC addresses.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi nodes often operate in infrastructure mode in which all communications go through a base station.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] *Ad hoc mode* refers to devices communicating directly with each other, without communicating with an access point.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A service set is the set of all the devices associated with a particular Wi-Fi network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Devices in a service set need not be on the same wavebands or channels.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A service set can be local, independent, extended, mesh, or a combination.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Each service set has an associated identifier, a 32-byte service set identifier (SSID), which identifies the network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The SSID is configured within the devices that are part of the network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A basic service set (BSS) is a group of stations that share the same wireless channel, SSID, and other settings that have wirelessly connected, usually to the same access point.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Each BSS is identified by a MAC address called the *BSSID*.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The IEEE does not test equipment for compliance with their standards.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance was formed in 1999 to establish and enforce standards for interoperability and backward compatibility, and to promote wireless local-area-network technology.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance enforces the use of the Wi-Fi brand to technologies based on the IEEE 802.11 standards from the IEEE.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Manufacturers with membership in the Wi-Fi Alliance, whose products pass the certification process, gain the right to mark those products with the Wi-Fi logo.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Specifically, the certification process requires conformance to the IEEE 802.11 radio standards, the WPA and WPA2 security standards, and the EAP authentication standard.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Certification may optionally include tests of IEEE 802.11 draft standards, interaction with cellular-phone technology in converged devices, and features relating to security set-up, multimedia, and power-saving.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Not every Wi-Fi device is submitted for certification.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The lack of Wi-Fi certification does not necessarily imply that a device is incompatible with other Wi-Fi devices.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance may or may not sanction derivative terms, such as Super Wi-Fi, coined by the US Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to describe proposed networking in the UHF TV band in the US.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Equipment frequently supports multiple versions of Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] To communicate, devices must use a common Wi-Fi version.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The versions differ between the radio wavebands they operate on, the radio bandwidth they occupy, the maximum data rates they can support and other details.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Some versions permit the use of multiple antennas, which permits greater speeds as well as reduced interference.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Historically, the equipment listed the versions of Wi-Fi supported using the name of the IEEE standards.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In 2018, the Wi-Fi Alliance introduced simplified Wi-Fi generational numbering to indicate equipment that supports Wi-Fi 4 (802.11n), Wi-Fi 5 (802.11ac) and Wi-Fi 6 (802.11ax).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] These generations have a high degree of backward compatibility with previous versions.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The alliance has stated that the generational level 4, 5, or 6 can be indicated in the user interface when connected, along with the signal strength.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi technology may be used to provide local network and Internet access to devices that are within Wi-Fi range of one or more routers that are connected to the Internet.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The coverage of one or more interconnected access points can extend from an area as small as a few rooms to as large as many square kilometres.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Coverage in the larger area may require a group of access points with overlapping coverage.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] For example, public outdoor Wi-Fi technology has been used successfully in wireless mesh networks in London.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi provides services in private homes, businesses, as well as in public spaces.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi hotspots may be set up either free of charge or commercially, often using a captive portal webpage for access.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Organizations, enthusiasts, authorities and businesses, such as airports, hotels, and restaurants, often provide free or paid-use hotspots to attract customers, to provide services to promote business in selected areas.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Routers often incorporate a digital subscriber line modem or a cable modem and a Wi-Fi access point, are frequently set up in homes and other buildings, to provide Internet access for the structure.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Similarly, battery-powered routers may include a mobile broadband modem and a Wi-Fi access point.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] When subscribed to a cellular data carrier, they allow nearby Wi-Fi stations to access the Internet.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A number of smartphones have a built-in mobile hotspot capability of this sort, though carriers often disable the feature, or charge a separate fee to enable it.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Standalone devices such as MiFi- and WiBro-branded devices provide the capability.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Some laptops that have a cellular modem card can also act as mobile Internet Wi-Fi access points.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Multiple traditional university campuses in the developed world provide at least partial Wi-Fi coverage.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Carnegie Mellon University built the first campus-wide wireless Internet network, called Wireless Andrew, at its Pittsburgh campus in 1993 before Wi-Fi branding existed.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A number of universities collaborate in providing Wi-Fi access to students and staff through the Eduroam international authentication infrastructure.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In the early 2000s, multiple cities around the world announced plans to construct citywide Wi-Fi networks.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] There are a number of successful examples; in 2004, Mysore (Mysuru) became India's first Wi-Fi-enabled city.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A company called WiFiyNet has set up hotspots in Mysore, covering the whole city and a few nearby villages.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Cloud, Florida and Sunnyvale, California, became the first cities in the United States to offer citywide free Wi-Fi (from MetroFi).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Minneapolis has generated $1.2 million in profit annually for its provider.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In May 2010, the then London mayor Boris Johnson pledged to have London-wide Wi-Fi by 2012.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Several boroughs including Westminster and Islington already had extensive outdoor Wi-Fi coverage at that point.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] New York City announced a city-wide campaign to convert old phone booths into digital kiosks in 2014.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The project, titled LinkNYC, has created a network of kiosks that serve as public Wi-Fi hotspots, high-definition screens and landlines.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Installation of the screens began in late 2015.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The city government plans to implement more than seven thousand kiosks over time, eventually making LinkNYC the largest and fastest public, government-operated Wi-Fi network in the world.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The UK has planned a similar project across major cities of the country, with the project's first implementation in the London Borough of Camden.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Officials in South Korea's capital Seoul were moving to provide free Internet access at more than 10,000 locations around the city, including outdoor public spaces, major streets, and densely populated residential areas.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Seoul was planning to grant leases to KT, LG Telecom, and SK Telecom.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The companies were supposed to invest $44 million in the project, which was to be completed in 2015.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi positioning systems use known positions of Wi-Fi hotspots to identify a device's location.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] It is used when GPS isn't suitable due to issues like signal interference or slow satellite acquisition.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This includes assisted GPS, urban hotspot databases, and indoor positioning systems.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi positioning relies on measuring signal strength (RSSI) and fingerprinting.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Parameters like SSID and MAC address are crucial for identifying access points.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The accuracy depends on nearby access points in the database.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Signal fluctuations can cause errors, which can be reduced with noise-filtering techniques.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] For low precision, integrating Wi-Fi data with geographical and time information has been proposed.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi RTT capability introduced in IEEE 802.11mc allows for positioning based on round trip time measurement, an improvement over the RSSI method.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The IEEE 802.11az standard promises further improvements in geolocation accuracy.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi sensing is used in applications such as motion detection and gesture recognition.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi stations communicate by sending each other data packets, blocks of data individually sent and delivered over radio on various channels.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] As with all radio, this is done by the modulation and demodulation of carrier waves.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Different versions of Wi-Fi use different techniques, 802.11b uses direct-sequence spread spectrum on a single carrier, whereas 802.11a, Wi-Fi 4, 5 and 6 use orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Channels are used half duplex and can be time-shared by multiple networks.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Any packet sent by one computer is locally received by stations tuned to that channel, even if that information is intended for just one destination.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Stations typically ignore information not addressed to them.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The use of the same channel also means that the data bandwidth is shared, so for example, available throughput to each device is halved when two stations are actively transmitting.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] As with other IEEE 802 LANs, stations come programmed with a globally unique 48-bit MAC address.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The MAC addresses are used to specify both the destination and the source of each data packet.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] On the reception of a transmission, the receiver uses the destination address to determine whether the transmission is relevant to the station or should be ignored.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A scheme known as carrier-sense multiple access with collision avoidance (CSMA/CA) governs the way stations share channels.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] With CSMA/CA stations attempt to avoid collisions by beginning transmission only after the channel is sensed to be idle, but then transmit their packet data in its entirety.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] CSMA/CA cannot completely prevent collisions, as two stations may sense the channel to be idle at the same time and thus begin transmission simultaneously.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A collision happens when a station receives signals from multiple stations on a channel at the same time.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This corrupts the transmitted data and can require stations to re-transmit.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The lost data and re-transmission reduces throughput, in some cases severely.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The 802.11 standard provides several distinct radio frequency ranges for use in Wi-Fi communications: 900 MHz, 2.4 GHz, 3.6 GHz, 4.9 GHz, 5 GHz, 6 GHz and 60 GHz bands.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Each range is divided into a multitude of channels.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In the standards, channels are numbered at 5 MHz spacing within a band (except in the 60 GHz band, where they are 2.16 GHz apart), and the number refers to the centre frequency of the channel.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Although channels are numbered at 5 MHz spacing, transmitters generally occupy at least 20 MHz, and standards allow for neighbouring channels to be bonded together to form a wider channel for higher throughput.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Countries apply their own regulations to the allowable channels, allowed users and maximum power levels within these frequency ranges.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] 802.11b/g/n can use the 2.4 GHz band, operating in the United States under FCC Part 15 rules and regulations.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In this frequency band, equipment may occasionally suffer interference from microwave ovens, cordless telephones, USB 3.0 hubs, Bluetooth and other devices.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Spectrum assignments and operational limitations are not consistent worldwide: Australia and Europe allow for an additional two channels (12, 13) beyond the 11 permitted in the United States for the 2.4 GHz band, while Japan has three more (12–14).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] 802.11a/h/j/n/ac/ax can use the 5 GHz U-NII band, which, for much of the world, offers at least 23 non-overlapping 20 MHz channels.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This is in contrast to the 2.4 GHz frequency band where the channels are only 5 MHz wide.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In general, lower frequencies have longer range but have less capacity.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The 5 GHz bands are absorbed to a greater degree by common building materials than the 2.4 GHz bands and usually give a shorter range.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] As 802.11 specifications evolved to support higher throughput, the protocols have become much more efficient in their bandwidth use.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Additionally, they have gained the ability to aggregate channels together to gain still more throughput where the bandwidth for additional channels is available.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] 802.11n allows for double radio spectrum bandwidth (40 MHz) per channel compared to 802.11a or 802.11g (20 MHz).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] 802.11n can be set to limit itself to 20 MHz bandwidth to prevent interference in dense communities.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In the 5 GHz band, 20 MHz, 40 MHz, 80 MHz, and 160 MHz channels are permitted with some restrictions, giving much faster connections.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi is part of the IEEE 802 protocol family.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The data is organized into 802.11 frames that are very similar to Ethernet frames at the data link layer, but with extra address fields.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] MAC addresses are used as network addresses for routing over the LAN.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi's MAC and physical layer (PHY) specifications are defined by IEEE 802.11 for modulating and receiving one or more carrier waves to transmit the data in the infrared, and 2.4, 3.6, 5, 6, or 60 GHz frequency bands.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] They are created and maintained by the IEEE LAN/MAN Standards Committee (IEEE 802).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The base version of the standard was released in 1997 and has had many subsequent amendments.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The standard and amendments provide the basis for wireless network products using the Wi-Fi brand.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] While each amendment is officially revoked when incorporated in the latest version of the standard, the corporate world tends to market to the revisions because they concisely denote capabilities of their products.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] As a result, in the market place, each revision tends to become its own standard.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In addition to 802.11, the IEEE 802 protocol family has specific provisions for Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] These are required because Ethernet's cable-based media are not usually shared, whereas with wireless all transmissions are received by all stations within the range that employ that radio channel.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] While Ethernet has essentially negligible error rates, wireless communication media are subject to significant interference.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Therefore, the accurate transmission is not guaranteed so delivery is, therefore, a best-effort delivery mechanism.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Because of this, for Wi-Fi, the Logical Link Control (LLC) specified by IEEE 802.2 employs Wi-Fi's media access control (MAC) protocols to manage retries without relying on higher levels of the protocol stack.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] For internetworking purposes, Wi-Fi is usually layered as a link layer below the internet layer of the Internet Protocol.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This means that nodes have an associated internet address and, with suitable connectivity, this allows full Internet access.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In infrastructure mode, which is the most common mode used, all communications go through a base station.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi also allows communications directly from one computer to another without an access point intermediary.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This is called *ad hoc* Wi-Fi transmission.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Different types of ad hoc networks exist.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In the simplest case, network nodes must talk directly to each other.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In more complex protocols nodes may forward packets, and nodes keep track of how to reach other nodes, even if they move around.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Ad hoc mode was first described by Chai Keong Toh in his 1996 patent of wireless ad hoc routing, implemented on Lucent WaveLAN 802.11a wireless on IBM ThinkPads over a size nodes scenario spanning a region of over a mile.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The success was recorded in *Mobile Computing* magazine (1999) and later published formally in *IEEE Transactions on Wireless Communications*, 2002 and *ACM SIGMETRICS Performance Evaluation Review*, 2001.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This wireless ad hoc network mode has proven popular with multiplayer video games on handheld game consoles, such as the Nintendo DS and PlayStation Portable.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] It is also popular on digital cameras, and other consumer electronics devices.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Some devices can also share their Internet connection using ad hoc, becoming hotspots or virtual routers.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Similarly, the Wi-Fi Alliance promotes the specification Wi-Fi Direct for file transfers and media sharing through a new discovery and security methodology.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Another mode of direct communication over Wi-Fi is Tunneled Direct Link Setup (TDLS), which enables two devices on the same Wi-Fi network to communicate directly, instead of via the access point.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] An Extended Service Set may be formed by deploying multiple access points that are configured with the same SSID and security settings.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi client devices typically connect to the access point that can provide the strongest signal within that service set.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Increasing the number of Wi-Fi access points for a network provides redundancy, better range, support for fast handover, and increased overall network capacity by using more channels or by defining smaller cells.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Except for the smallest implementations (such as home or small office networks), Wi-Fi implementations have moved toward *thin* access points, with more of the network intelligence housed in a centralized network appliance, relegating individual access points to the role of dumb transceivers.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Outdoor applications may use mesh topologies.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi operational range depends on factors such as the frequency band, modulation technique, transmitter power output, receiver sensitivity, antenna gain and type, and propagation and interference characteristics in the environment.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] At longer distances, speed is typically reduced.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Compared to cell phones and similar technology, Wi-Fi transmitters are low-power devices.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In general, the maximum amount of power that a Wi-Fi device can transmit is limited by local regulations, such as FCC Part 15 in the US.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Equivalent isotropically radiated power (EIRP) in the European Union is limited to 20 dBm (100 mW).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi, however, has higher power compared to some other standards designed to support wireless personal area network applications.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] For example, Bluetooth provides a much shorter propagation range between 1 and 100 metres (1 and 100 yards) and so in general has a lower power consumption.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Other low-power technologies such as Zigbee have fairly long range, but much lower data rate.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The high power consumption of Wi-Fi makes battery life in some mobile devices a concern.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] On wireless routers with detachable antennas, it is possible to improve range by fitting upgraded antennas.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] An access point compliant with either 802.11b or 802.11g, using the stock omnidirectional antenna might have a range of 0.1 km.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The same radio with an external semi-parabolic antenna (15 dB gain) with a similarly equipped receiver at the far end might have a range of over 32 km.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Higher gain rating (dBi) indicates deviation from a theoretical, perfect isotropic radiator toward a directional antenna, and therefore the antenna can project or accept a usable signal further in particular directions, as compared to a similar output power on a more isotropic antenna.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] For example, an 8 dBi antenna used with a 100 mW driver has a similar horizontal range to a 6 dBi antenna being driven at 500 mW.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This assumes that radiation in the vertical direction is not useful for communications.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi 4 and higher standards allow devices to have multiple antennas on transmitters and receivers.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Multiple antennas enable the equipment to exploit multipath propagation on the same frequency bands, giving higher speeds and more than doubled range.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi 5 standard uses the 5 GHz band exclusively, and is capable of multi-station WLAN throughput of at least 1 gigabit per second, and a single station throughput of at least 500 Mbit/s.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This standard uses several signal processing techniques such as multi-user MIMO and 4 × 4 spatial multiplexing streams, and wide channel bandwidth (160 MHz) to achieve its gigabit throughput.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] With Wi-Fi signals, line-of-sight usually works best, but signals can absorb, reflect, refract, diffract and fade through and around structures, both man-made and natural.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi signals are very strongly affected by metallic structures (including rebar in concrete, low-e coatings in glazing), rock structures (including marble) and water (such as found in vegetation).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Due to the complex nature of radio propagation at typical Wi-Fi frequencies, particularly around trees and buildings, algorithms can only approximately predict Wi-Fi signal strength for any given area in relation to a transmitter.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Performance associated with long-range Wi-Fi is more easily predicted, since longer links typically operate line-of-sight from towers that transmit above the surrounding foliage.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Distance records (using non-standard devices) include 382 km (237 mi) in June 2007, held by Ermanno Pietrosemoli and EsLaRed of Venezuela, transferring about 3 MB/sec of data between the mountain-tops of El Águila and Platillon.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The Swedish National Space Agency transferred data 420 km (260 mi), using 6 watt amplifiers to reach an overhead stratospheric balloon.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi connections can be blocked or the network throughput lowered by having other devices in the same area.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi protocols are designed to share the radio bandwidth reasonably fairly.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Nevertheless, Wi-Fi networks are still susceptible to the hidden node and exposed node problems.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A standard speed Wi-Fi signal occupies five channels in the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Adjacent-channel interference can be caused by overlapping channels.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Any two channel numbers that differ by five or more, such as 2 and 7, do not overlap.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Channels 1, 6, and 11 are the only *group of three* non-overlapping channels in North America.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] However, whether the overlap is significant depends on physical spacing.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Channels that differ by four interfere a negligible amount – much less than reusing channels (which causes co-channel interference) – if transmitters are at least a few metres apart.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In Europe and Japan where channel 13 is available, using Channels 1, 5, 9, and 13 for 802.11g and 802.11n is viable and recommended.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] However, multiple 2.4 GHz 802.11b and 802.11g access points default to the same channel on initial startup, contributing to congestion on certain channels.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi pollution, or an excessive number of access points in the area, can prevent access and interfere with other devices' use of other access points, as well as decreasing overall signal-to-noise ratio (SNR).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] These issues can become a problem in high-density areas, such as large apartment complexes or office buildings with multiple Wi-Fi access points.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] It is also an issue when municipalities or other large entities (such as universities) seek to provide large area coverage.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Other devices use the 2.4 GHz band: microwave ovens, ISM band devices, security cameras, Zigbee devices, Bluetooth devices, video senders, cordless phones, baby monitors, and, in some countries, amateur radio, all of which can cause significant additional interference.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] On some 5 GHz bands interference from radar systems can occur in some places.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Access points that support those bands employ dynamic frequency selection, which listens for radar, and if detected, will not permit transmission on that band.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] These bands can be used by low-power transmitters without a licence, and with few restrictions.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] However, while unintended interference is common, users who have been found to cause deliberate interference (particularly for attempting to locally monopolize these bands for commercial purposes) have been issued large fines.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Various layer-2 variants of IEEE 802.11 have different characteristics.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Across all flavours of 802.11, maximum achievable throughputs are either given based on measurements under ideal conditions or in the layer-2 data rates.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This, however, does not apply to typical deployments in which data are transferred between two endpoints, of which at least one is typically connected to a wired infrastructure.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This means that typically data frames pass an 802.11 (WLAN) medium and are converted to 802.3 (Ethernet) or vice versa.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Due to the difference in the frame (header) lengths of these two media, the packet size of an application determines the speed of the data transfer.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This means that an application that uses small packets (e.g., VoIP) creates a data flow with higher overhead and lower information rate.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Other factors that contribute to the overall application data rate include the energy with which the wireless signal is received.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi allows wireless deployment of local area networks (LANs).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Also, spaces where cables cannot be run, such as outdoor areas and historical buildings, can host wireless LANs.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] However, building walls of certain materials, such as stone with high metal content, can block Wi-Fi signals.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A Wi-Fi device is a short-range wireless device.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi devices are fabricated on RF CMOS integrated circuit (RF circuit) chips.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Since the early 2000s, manufacturers are building wireless network adapters into most laptops.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The price of chipsets for Wi-Fi continues to drop, making it an economical networking option included in ever more devices.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Different competitive brands of access points and client network-interfaces can inter-operate at a basic level of service.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Products designated as "Wi-Fi Certified" by the Wi-Fi Alliance are backward compatible.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Unlike mobile phones, any standard Wi-Fi device works anywhere in the world.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A wireless access point (WAP) connects a group of wireless devices to an adjacent wired LAN.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] An access point resembles a network hub, relaying data between connected wireless devices in addition to a (usually) single connected wired device, most often an Ethernet hub or switch, allowing wireless devices to communicate with other wired devices.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wireless adapters allow devices to connect to a wireless network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] These adapters connect to devices using various external or internal interconnects such as mini PCIe (mPCIe, M.2), USB, ExpressCard and previously PCI, Cardbus, and PC Card.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] As of 2010, most newer laptop computers come equipped with built-in internal adapters.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wireless routers integrate a Wireless Access Point, Ethernet switch, and internal router firmware application that provides IP routing, NAT, and DNS forwarding through an integrated WAN-interface.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A wireless router allows wired and wireless Ethernet LAN devices to connect to a (usually) single WAN device such as a cable modem, DSL modem, or optical modem.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A wireless router allows all three devices, mainly the access point and router, to be configured through one central utility.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This utility is usually an integrated web server that is accessible to wired and wireless LAN clients and often optionally to WAN clients.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This utility may also be an application that is run on a computer, as is the case with as Apple's AirPort, which is managed with the AirPort Utility on macOS and iOS.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wireless network bridges can act to connect two networks to form a single network at the data-link layer over Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The main standard is the wireless distribution system (WDS).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wireless bridging can connect a wired network to a wireless network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A bridge differs from an access point: an access point typically connects wireless devices to one wired network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A dual-band wireless bridge can also be used to enable 5 GHz wireless network operation on a device that only supports 2.4 GHz wireless and has a wired Ethernet port.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wireless range-extenders or wireless repeaters can extend the range of an existing wireless network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Strategically placed range-extenders can elongate a signal area or allow for the signal area to reach around barriers such as those pertaining in L-shaped corridors.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wireless devices connected through repeaters suffer from an increased latency for each hop, and there may be a reduction in the maximum available data throughput.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Besides, the effect of additional users using a network employing wireless range-extenders is to consume the available bandwidth faster than would be the case whereby a single user migrates around a network employing extenders.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] For this reason, wireless range-extenders work best in networks supporting low traffic throughput requirements, such as for cases whereby a single user with a Wi-Fi-equipped tablet migrates around the combined extended and non-extended portions of the total connected network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Also, a wireless device connected to any of the repeaters in the chain has data throughput limited by the "weakest link" in the chain between the connection origin and connection end.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Networks using wireless extenders are more prone to degradation from interference from neighbouring access points that border portions of the extended network and that happen to occupy the same channel as the extended network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The security standard, Wi-Fi Protected Setup, allows embedded devices with a limited graphical user interface to connect to the Internet with ease.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi Protected Setup has 2 configurations: The Push Button configuration and the PIN configuration.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] These embedded devices are also called The Internet of things and are low-power, battery-operated embedded systems.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Several Wi-Fi manufacturers design chips and modules for embedded Wi-Fi, such as GainSpan.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Increasingly in the last few years (particularly as of 2007), embedded Wi-Fi modules have become available that incorporate a real-time operating system and provide a simple means of wirelessly enabling any device that can communicate via a serial port.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This allows the design of simple monitoring devices.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] An example is a portable ECG device monitoring a patient at home.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] This Wi-Fi-enabled device can communicate via the Internet.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] These Wi-Fi modules are designed by OEMs so that implementers need only minimal Wi-Fi knowledge to provide Wi-Fi connectivity for their products.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In June 2014, Texas Instruments introduced the first ARM Cortex-M4 microcontroller with an onboard dedicated Wi-Fi MCU, the SimpleLink CC3200.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] It makes embedded systems with Wi-Fi connectivity possible to build as single-chip devices, which reduces their cost and minimum size, making it more practical to build wireless-networked controllers into inexpensive ordinary objects.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The main issue with wireless network security is its simplified access to the network compared to traditional wired networks such as Ethernet.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] With wired networking, one must either gain access to a building (physically connecting into the internal network), or break through an external firewall.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] To access Wi-Fi, one must merely be within the range of the Wi-Fi network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Most business networks protect sensitive data and systems by attempting to disallow external access.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Enabling wireless connectivity reduces security if the network uses inadequate or no encryption.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] An attacker who has gained access to a Wi-Fi network router can initiate a DNS spoofing attack against any other user of the network by forging a response before the queried DNS server has a chance to reply.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A common measure to deter unauthorized users involves hiding the access point's name by disabling the SSID broadcast.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] While effective against the casual user, it is ineffective as a security method because the SSID is broadcast in the clear in response to a client SSID query.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Another method is to only allow computers with known MAC addresses to join the network, but determined eavesdroppers may be able to join the network by spoofing an authorized address.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) encryption was designed to protect against casual snooping but it is no longer considered secure.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Tools such as AirSnort or Aircrack-ng can quickly recover WEP encryption keys.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Because of WEP's weakness the Wi-Fi Alliance approved Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) which uses TKIP.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] WPA was specifically designed to work with older equipment usually through a firmware upgrade.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Though more secure than WEP, WPA has known vulnerabilities.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The more secure WPA2 using Advanced Encryption Standard was introduced in 2004 and is supported by most new Wi-Fi devices.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In 2017, a flaw in the WPA2 protocol was discovered, allowing a key replay attack, known as KRACK.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A flaw in a feature added to Wi-Fi in 2007, called Wi-Fi Protected Setup (WPS), let WPA and WPA2 security be bypassed.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The only remedy as of 2011 was to turn off Wi-Fi Protected Setup, which is not always possible.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Virtual private networks can be used to improve the confidentiality of data carried through Wi-Fi networks, especially public Wi-Fi networks.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A URI using the Wi-Fi scheme can specify the SSID, encryption type, password/passphrase, and if the SSID is hidden or not, so users can follow links from QR codes, for instance, to join networks without having to manually enter the data.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A MeCard-like format is supported by Android and iOS 11+.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi access points typically default to an encryption-free (*open*) mode.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Novice users benefit from a zero-configuration device that works out-of-the-box, but this default does not enable any wireless security, providing open wireless access to a LAN.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] To turn security on requires the user to configure the device, usually via a software graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] On unencrypted Wi-Fi networks connecting devices can monitor and record data (including personal information).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Such networks can only be secured by using other means of protection, such as a VPN, or Hypertext Transfer Protocol over Transport Layer Security (HTTPS).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The older wireless-encryption standard, Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP), has been shown easily breakable even when correctly configured.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) encryption, which became available in devices in 2003, aimed to solve this problem.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) ratified in 2004 is considered secure, provided a strong passphrase is used.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] The 2003 version of WPA has not been considered secure since it was superseded by WPA2 in 2004.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In 2018, WPA3 was announced as a replacement for WPA2, increasing security; it rolled out on 26 June.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Piggybacking refers to access to a wireless Internet connection by bringing one's computer within the range of another's wireless connection, and using that service without the subscriber's explicit permission or knowledge.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] During the early popular adoption of 802.11, providing open access points for anyone within range to use was encouraged to cultivate wireless community networks, particularly since people on average use only a fraction of their downstream bandwidth at any given time.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Recreational logging and mapping of other people's access points have become known as wardriving.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Indeed, many access points are intentionally installed without security turned on so that they can be used as a free service.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Providing access to one's Internet connection in this fashion may breach the Terms of Service or contract with the Internet service provider (ISP).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] These activities do not result in sanctions in most jurisdictions; however, legislation and case law differ considerably across the world.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A proposal to leave graffiti describing available services was called warchalking.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Piggybacking often occurs unintentionally – a technically unfamiliar user might not change the default "unsecured" settings to their access point and operating systems can be configured to connect automatically to any available wireless network.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] A user who happens to start up a laptop in the vicinity of an access point may find the computer has joined the network without any visible indication.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] Moreover, a user intending to join one network may instead end up on another one if the latter has a stronger signal.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] In combination with automatic discovery of other network resources (see DHCP and Zeroconf) this could lead wireless users to send sensitive data to the wrong middle-man when seeking a destination (see man-in-the-middle attack).
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p01] For example, a user could inadvertently use an unsecured network to log into a website, thereby making the login credentials available to anyone listening, if the website uses an insecure protocol such as plain HTTP without TLS.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] Wireless Internet access has become much more embedded in society.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] It has thus changed how the society functions in a number of ways.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] As of 2017 over half the world did not have access to the Internet, prominently rural areas in developing nations.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] Technology that has been implemented in more developed nations is often costly and energy inefficient.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] This has led to developing nations using more low-tech networks, frequently implementing renewable power sources that can solely be maintained through solar power, creating a network that is resistant to disruptions such as power outages.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] For instance, in 2007, a 450-kilometre (280 mi) network between Cabo Pantoja and Iquitos in Peru was erected in which all equipment is powered only by solar panels.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] These long-range Wi-Fi networks have two main uses: offer Internet access to populations in isolated villages, and to provide healthcare to isolated communities.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] In the case of the latter example, it connects the central hospital in Iquitos to 15 medical outposts which are intended for remote diagnosis.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] Access to Wi-Fi in public spaces such as cafés or parks allows people, in particular freelancers, to work remotely.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] While the accessibility of Wi-Fi is the strongest factor when choosing a place to work (75% of people would choose a place that provides Wi-Fi over one that does not), other factors influence the choice of specific hotspots.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] These vary from the accessibility of other resources, like books, the location of the workplace, and the social aspect of meeting other people in the same place.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] Moreover, the increase of people working from public places results in more customers for local businesses thus providing an economic stimulus to the area.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] Additionally, in the same study it has been noted that wireless connection provides more freedom of movement while working.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] Both when working at home or from the office it allows the displacement between different rooms or areas.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] In some offices (notably Cisco offices in New York) the employees do not have assigned desks but can work from any office connecting their laptop to Wi-Fi hotspot.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] The Internet has become an integral part of living.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] As of 2016, 81.9% of American households have Internet access.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] Additionally, 89% of American households with broadband connect via wireless technologies.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] 72.9% of American households have Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] Wi-Fi networks have also affected how the interior of homes and hotels are arranged.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] For instance, architects have described that their clients no longer wanted only one room as their home office, but would like to work near the fireplace or have the possibility to work in different rooms.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] This contradicts architect's pre-existing ideas of the use of rooms that they designed.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] Additionally, some hotels have noted that guests prefer to stay in certain rooms since they receive a stronger Wi-Fi signal.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] The World Health Organization (WHO) says, "no health effects are expected from exposure to RF fields from base stations and wireless networks", but notes that they promote research into effects from other RF sources.
[src:wifi-standards/wi-fi-p02] The United Kingdom's Health Protection Agency reported in 2007 that exposure to Wi-Fi for a year results in the "same amount of radiation from a 20-minute mobile phone call".
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] A **wireless LAN** (**WLAN**) is a wireless computer network that links two or more devices using wireless communication to form a local area network (LAN) within a limited area such as a home, school, computer laboratory, campus, or office building.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] This gives users the ability to move around within the area and remain connected to the network.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Through a gateway, a WLAN can also provide a connection to the wider Internet.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Wireless LANs based on the IEEE 802.11 standards are the most widely used computer networks in the world.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] These are commonly called Wi-Fi, which is a trademark belonging to the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] They are used for home and small office networks that link together laptop computers, printers, smartphones, Web TVs and gaming devices through a wireless network router, which in turn may link them to the Internet.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Hotspots provided by routers at restaurants, coffee shops, hotels, libraries, and airports allow consumers to access the internet with portable wireless devices.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Norman Abramson, a professor at the University of Hawaiʻi, developed the world's first wireless computer communication network, ALOHAnet.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The system became operational in 1971 and included seven computers deployed over four islands to communicate with the central computer on the Oahu island without using phone lines.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Wireless LAN hardware initially cost so much that it was only used as an alternative to cabled LAN in places where cabling was difficult or impossible.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Early development included industry-specific solutions and proprietary protocols, but at the end of the 1990s these were replaced by technical standards, primarily the various versions of IEEE 802.11 (in products using the Wi-Fi brand name).
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] In 1990 CSIRO researchers began working on strategies for increasing the efficacy of wireless networks, specifically targeting methods of reducing the delay of receiving information.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The team, which built upon John O´Sullivan`s findings on the Fourier Transform in the 1970s, has been credited as an integral part of the development of the modern infrastructure used globally.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Beginning in 1991, a European alternative known as HiperLAN/1 was pursued by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) with a first version approved in 1996.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] This was followed by a HiperLAN/2 functional specification with ATM influences accomplished February 2000.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Neither European standard achieved the commercial success of 802.11, although much of the work on HiperLAN/2 has survived in the physical specification (PHY) for IEEE 802.11a, which is nearly identical to the PHY of HiperLAN/2.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] It operates in both the 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz bands at a maximum data transfer rate of 600 Mbit/s.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Most newer routers are *dual-band* and able to utilize both wireless bands.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] This allows data communications to avoid the crowded 2.4 GHz band, which is also shared with Bluetooth devices and microwave ovens.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The 5 GHz band also has more channels than the 2.4 GHz band, permitting a greater number of devices to share the space.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Not all WLAN channels are available in all regions.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] A HomeRF group formed in 1997 to promote a technology aimed at residential use, but it disbanded in January 2003.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] All components that can connect into a wireless medium in a network are referred to as stations.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] All stations are equipped with wireless network interface controllers.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Wireless stations fall into two categories: wireless access points (WAPs) and clients.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] WAPs are base stations for the wireless network.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] They transmit and receive radio frequencies for wireless-enabled devices to communicate with.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Wireless clients can be mobile devices such as laptops, personal digital assistants, VoIP phones and other smartphones, or non-portable devices such as desktop computers, printers, and workstations that are equipped with a wireless network interface.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The basic service set (BSS) is a set of all stations that can communicate with each other at PHY layer.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Every BSS has an identification (ID) called the BSSID, which is the MAC address of the access point servicing the BSS.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] There are two types of BSS: Independent BSS (also referred to as IBSS), and infrastructure BSS.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] An independent BSS (IBSS) is an ad hoc network that contains no access points, which means they cannot connect to any other basic service set.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] In an IBSS the STAs are configured in ad hoc (peer-to-peer) mode.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] An extended service set (ESS) is a set of connected BSSs.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Access points in an ESS are connected by a distribution system.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Each ESS has an ID called the SSID which is a 32-byte (maximum) character string.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] A distribution system (DS) connects access points in an extended service set.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The concept of a DS can be used to increase network coverage through roaming between cells.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Current wireless distribution systems are mostly based on WDS or Mesh protocols, though other systems are in use.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The IEEE 802.11 has two basic modes of operation: *infrastructure* and *ad hoc* mode.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] In ad hoc mode, mobile units communicate directly peer-to-peer.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] In infrastructure mode, mobile units communicate through a wireless access point (WAP) that also serves as a bridge to other networks such as a local area network or the Internet.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Many access points will also offer Wi-Fi Protected Setup, a quick, but no longer considered secure, method of joining a new device to an encrypted network.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Most Wi-Fi networks are deployed in *infrastructure mode*.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] In infrastructure mode, wireless clients, such as laptops and smartphones, connect to the WAP to join the network.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The WAP usually has a wired network connection and may have permanent wireless connections to other WAPs.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] WAPs are usually fixed and provide service to their client nodes within range.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Some networks will have multiple WAPs using the same SSID and security arrangement.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] In that case, connecting to any WAP on that network joins the client to the network, and the client software will try to choose the WAP that gives the best service, such as the WAP with the strongest signal.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] An ad hoc network is a network where stations communicate only peer-to-peer (P2P).
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] There is no base and no one gives permission to talk.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] This is accomplished using the Independent Basic Service Set (IBSS).
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] A Wi-Fi Direct network is a different type of wireless network where stations communicate peer-to-peer.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] In a peer-to-peer network wireless devices within range of each other can discover and communicate directly without involving central access points.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] In a Wi-Fi P2P group, the group owner operates as an access point and all other devices are clients.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] There are two main methods to establish a group owner in the Wi-Fi Direct group.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] In one approach, the user sets up a P2P group owner manually.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] This method is also known as *autonomous group owner* (*autonomous GO*).
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] In the second method, called *negotiation-based group creation*, two devices compete based on the group owner intent value.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The device with higher intent value becomes a group owner and the second device becomes a client.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] IEEE 802.11 defines the PHY and medium access control (MAC) layers based on carrier-sense multiple access with collision avoidance (CSMA/CA).
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] This is in contrast to Ethernet which uses carrier-sense multiple access with collision detection (CSMA/CD).
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The 802.11 specification includes provisions designed to minimize collisions because mobile units have to contend with the hidden node problem where two mobile units may both be in range of a common access point, but out of range of each other.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] A bridge can be used to connect networks, typically of different types.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] A wireless Ethernet bridge allows the connection of devices on a wired Ethernet network to a wireless network.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The bridge acts as the connection point to the wireless LAN.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] A wireless distribution system (WDS) enables the wireless interconnection of access points in an IEEE 802.11 network.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] It allows a wireless network to be expanded using multiple access points without the need for a wired backbone to link them, as is traditionally required.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The notable advantage of a WDS over some other solutions is that it preserves the MAC addresses of client packets across links between access points.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] An access point can be either a main, relay, or remote base station.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] A main base station is typically connected to the wired Ethernet.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] A relay base station relays data between remote base stations, wireless clients or other relay stations to either a main or another relay base station.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] A remote base station accepts connections from wireless clients and passes them to relay or main stations.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Because data is forwarded wirelessly, consuming wireless bandwidth, throughput in this method is halved for wireless clients not connected to a main base station.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] Connections between base stations are done at layer-2 and do not involve or require layer-3 IP addresses.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] WDS capability may also be referred to as repeater mode because it appears to bridge and accept wireless clients at the same time (unlike traditional bridging).
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] All base stations in a WDS must be configured to use the same radio channel and share WEP keys or WPA keys if they are used.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] They can be configured to different service set identifiers.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] WDS also requires that every base station be configured to forward to others in the system as mentioned above.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] **External roaming:** The MS (client) moves into a WLAN of another wireless Internet service provider (WISP) and takes their services.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] The user can use a foreign network independently from their home network, provided that the foreign network allows visiting users on their network.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] There must be special authentication and billing systems for mobile services in a foreign network.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] WLAN signals often extends beyond the boundaries of a building and can create coverage where it is unwanted, offering a channel through which non-residents or other unauthorized people could compromise a system and retrieve personal data.
[src:wifi-standards/wireless-lan] To prevent this, it is usually sufficient to enforce the use of authentication, encryption, or a VPN that requires a password for network connectivity.
